Part A: Understanding Fractions

Shade the model to represent 3/4.

Shade two different models that both represent 1/2.

Write the fraction represented on the number line:
(Teacher inserts number line showing a point between 0 and 1.)

Part B: Equivalent Fractions

Write two equivalent fractions for 3/5.

Fill in the blank to make an equivalent fraction:
4/6 = ___ / 9

Which two fractions are equivalent?
a. 2/3
b. 4/9
c. 6/9
d. 8/12

Part C: Comparing Fractions

Compare using <, >, or =:
a. 3/8 ___ 5/8
b. 2/3 ___ 3/4
c. 5/6 ___ 4/6
d. 7/12 ___ 2/3

Order from least to greatest:
1/4, 5/6, 2/3

Part D: Mixed Numbers & Improper Fractions

Convert to an improper fraction:
3 1/4 = ?

Convert to a mixed number:
17/5 = ?

Draw a model showing 2 1/2.

Part E: Adding & Subtracting Fractions

With like denominators:
a. 3/10 + 4/10 =
b. 7/8 − 3/8 =

With unlike denominators:
a. 1/4 + 2/3 =
b. 5/6 − 1/3 =

Part F: Word Problems

A recipe needs 3/4 cup of sugar and 2/4 cup of flour.
How much more sugar is used than flour?

You ran 2/3 of a mile in the morning and 1/6 of a mile in the evening.
How far did you run in total?